&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://errorcode.excellentwiki.com/languages/javascript/err-http2-session/"&gt;ERR_HTTP2_SESSION&lt;/a&gt; — HTTP/2 session error.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://errorcode.excellentwiki.com/languages/javascript/err-http2-stream/"&gt;ERR_HTTP2_STREAM_CLOSED&lt;/a&gt; — stream already closed.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://errorcode.excellentwiki.com/languages/javascript/err_stream_destroyed/"&gt;ERR_STREAM_DESTROYED&lt;/a&gt; — stream destroyed.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;</description></item><item><title>[Solution] Python ConnectionResetError — Connection Reset Fix</title><link>https://errorcode.excellentwiki.com/languages/python/connectionreseterror/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://errorcode.excellentwiki.com/languages/python/connectionreseterror/</guid><description>&lt;h1 id="connectionreseterror--connection-reset-fix"&gt;ConnectionResetError — Connection Reset Fix&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;p&gt;A &lt;code&gt;ConnectionResetError&lt;/code&gt; is raised when a connection is reset by the remote host (the other end sends a TCP RST packet). It&amp;rsquo;s a subclass of &lt;code&gt;ConnectionError&lt;/code&gt;, which is a subclass of &lt;code&gt;OSError&lt;/code&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id="description"&gt;Description&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;When the remote end of a connection actively resets it — typically by calling &lt;code&gt;close()&lt;/code&gt; on its socket or by the process crashing — Python raises &lt;code&gt;ConnectionResetError&lt;/code&gt; on the local side. This differs from &lt;code&gt;ConnectionAbortedError&lt;/code&gt; (where the local host initiates the abort) and &lt;code&gt;BrokenPipeError&lt;/code&gt; (which occurs during write operations).&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>[Solution] Rust Connection Reset — Connection Reset by Peer</title><link>https://errorcode.excellentwiki.com/languages/rust/connection-reset/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://errorcode.excellentwiki.com/languages/rust/connection-reset/</guid><description>&lt;h1 id="connection-reset--connection-reset-by-peer"&gt;Connection Reset — Connection Reset by Peer&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;p&gt;An IO error with the message &amp;ldquo;Connection reset by peer (os error 104)&amp;rdquo; occurs when the remote side of a TCP connection sends a RST packet, abruptly closing the connection.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id="description"&gt;Description&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;A connection reset happens when:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;The server process crashes or is killed.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;The server&amp;rsquo;s OS closes the connection abruptly.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;A firewall or load balancer drops the connection.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Network issues cause the connection to become invalid.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Unlike &amp;ldquo;connection refused&amp;rdquo; (which means the server isn&amp;rsquo;t listening), &amp;ldquo;connection reset&amp;rdquo; means a connection was established but then forcibly closed. The error code is 104 (&lt;code&gt;ECONNRESET&lt;/code&gt;).&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>[Solution] Rust Connection Reset — Peer Reset Connection</title><link>https://errorcode.excellentwiki.com/languages/rust/connection-reset-2/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://errorcode.excellentwiki.com/languages/rust/connection-reset-2/</guid><description>&lt;h1 id="connection-reset--peer-reset-connection"&gt;Connection Reset — Peer Reset Connection&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;p&gt;An IO error with the message &amp;ldquo;Connection reset by peer (os error 104)&amp;rdquo; occurs when the remote end of an established TCP connection sends a RST packet, forcibly closing it.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id="description"&gt;Description&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;A connection reset means a connection &lt;em&gt;was&lt;/em&gt; established but was then abruptly terminated. The peer (server or client) sent a TCP RST instead of a graceful FIN. Error code 104 (&lt;code&gt;ECONNRESET&lt;/code&gt;).&lt;/p&gt;
